Vice President Kamala Harris visited Durham, North Carolina to highlight the work being done to support seniors in the community. She thanked Governor Roy Cooper and other leaders for their partnership in addressing issues affecting seniors, such as elder abuse and the high cost of healthcare. Harris announced that starting next year, the cost of insulin prescriptions for people on Medicare will be capped at $35 per month. She also discussed the administration's efforts to lower the cost of prescription drugs by allowing Medicare to negotiate prices with pharmaceutical companies. In addition, Harris mentioned the availability of over-the-counter hearing aids to reduce the financial burden on seniors with hearing loss. Lastly, she emphasized the importance of capping out-of-pocket prescription drug costs for Medicare recipients at $2,000 per year, starting in 2025. Harris concluded by stating that access to affordable healthcare is a right and should not be a privilege based on financial means.